use strict;
use warnings;

use Bedrock::Constants qw(:booleans);
use Crypt::URandom qw(urandom);
use Data::Dumper;
use Role::Tiny;

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Generates or retrieves the current CSRF token
########################################################################
sub csrf_token {
########################################################################
  my ($obj) = @_;

  my $self = tied %{$obj} || $obj;

  if ( !$self->{data}->{prefs}->{csrf_token} ) {
    my $token = unpack 'H*', urandom(32);
    $self->{data}->{prefs}->{csrf_token} = $token;
  }

  return $self->{data}->{prefs}->{csrf_token};
}

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Verifies a submitted token against the stored session token
########################################################################
sub check_csrf_token {
########################################################################
  my ( $obj, $submitted_token ) = @_;

  my $self = tied %{$obj} || $obj;

  return $FALSE
    if !$submitted_token;

  # Retrieve the authoritative token from the session store
  my $stored_token = $self->{data}->{prefs}->{csrf_token};

  return $FALSE
    if !$stored_token;

  # Direct string comparison is sufficient and secure here
  my $result = $submitted_token eq $stored_token;

  $obj->rotate_csrf_token;  # rotate immediately

  return $result;
}

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Rotates the token (useful after login/logout to prevent fixation)
########################################################################
sub rotate_csrf_token {
########################################################################
  my ($obj) = @_;

  my $self = tied %{$obj} // $obj;

  delete $self->{data}->{prefs}->{csrf_token};

  # Generate a new one immediately
  return $obj->csrf_token;
}

1;

## no critic (RequirePodSections)

__END__

=pod

=head1 NAME

Bedrock::CSRF - CSRF token generation, validation, and rotation for Bedrock sessions

=head1 SYNOPSIS

In a Bedrock template (form with hidden token):

 <form method="POST" action="/submit">
   <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token"
          value="<var $session.csrf_token()>">
   <input type="text" name="username">
   <button type="submit">Submit</button>
 </form>

In the receiving template or service (validation):

 <if $session.check_csrf_token($input.csrf_token)>
   <!-- token valid, process the form -->
 <else>
   <!-- token invalid or missing, reject the request -->
   <raise "CSRF token validation failed">
 </if>

In Perl (within a Bedrock service or plugin):

 my $token  = $session->csrf_token;
 my $valid  = $session->check_csrf_token($submitted_token);
 my $rotated = $session->rotate_csrf_token;

=head1 DESCRIPTION

C<Bedrock::CSRF> is a L<Role::Tiny> role that provides Cross-Site
Request Forgery protection for Bedrock session objects. It is
composed into L<BLM::Startup::BaseSession>, which means all Bedrock
session managers (including L<BLM::Startup::SessionManager> and its
subclasses) automatically have CSRF support.

The role stores the CSRF token inside the session's preferences hash
(C<< $self->{data}->{prefs}->{csrf_token} >>), so tokens persist
across requests for the lifetime of the session and are automatically
saved and restored by the session manager's serialization.

Tokens are generated using 32 bytes from L<Crypt::URandom>,
producing a 64-character hex string. This provides 256 bits of
cryptographically secure randomness, making tokens resistant to
brute-force guessing.

=head1 METHODS

=head2 csrf_token

 my $token = $session->csrf_token;

Returns the current CSRF token for the session. If no token exists
(new session or after rotation), one is generated automatically and
stored in the session.

Call this method when rendering forms to embed the token as a hidden
field. The same token is returned on repeated calls within the same
session until it is rotated.

=head2 check_csrf_token

 my $valid = $session->check_csrf_token($submitted_token);

Validates a submitted token against the token stored in the session.
Returns true if the tokens match, false otherwise. Returns false
immediately if either the submitted token or the stored token is
empty or undefined.

B<The token is rotated after every call to C<check_csrf_token>>,
regardless of whether validation succeeded. This prevents replay
attacks where an attacker reuses a previously intercepted token.
The next call to C<csrf_token> will return the new token.

=head2 rotate_csrf_token

 my $new_token = $session->rotate_csrf_token;

Deletes the current CSRF token and generates a new one. Returns
the new token. Use this explicitly after login, logout, or privilege
escalation to prevent token fixation attacks.

You do not normally need to call this directly -- C<check_csrf_token>
rotates automatically after each validation attempt.

=head1 USAGE PATTERNS

=head2 Standard Form Protection

The simplest pattern: embed the token in a hidden field and validate
on submission.

 <!-- form.roc -->
 <form method="POST" action="/process">
   <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token"
          value="<var $session.csrf_token()>">
   ...
 </form>

 <!-- process.roc -->
 <unless $session.check_csrf_token($input.csrf_token)>
   <raise "invalid or missing CSRF token">
 </unless>
 <!-- safe to process the form -->

=head2 AJAX with Token Refresh

Since C<check_csrf_token> rotates the token after validation, AJAX
handlers must return the new token to the client. A common pattern
is to include the new token in every JSON response:

 <!-- api handler (jroc) -->
 <if $env.REQUEST_METHOD --eq 'POST'>
   <unless $session.check_csrf_token($input.csrf_token)>
     <raise "CSRF validation failed">
   </unless>
 </if>

 <!-- include fresh token in response -->
 <hash:response status "ok" csrf_token $session.csrf_token()>
 <var --json $response>

The client-side JavaScript updates the stored token from the
response:

 fetch('/api/action', {
   method: 'POST',
   headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
   body: JSON.stringify({ csrf_token: currentToken, ...data })
 })
 .then(r => r.json())
 .then(data => {
   currentToken = data.csrf_token;  // refresh for next request
 });

=head2 Token Rotation on Login

Rotate the token after authentication to prevent session fixation:

 <!-- after successful login -->
 <null $session.rotate_csrf_token()>

=head1 SECURITY NOTES

=over 4

=item *

Tokens are 64 hex characters (256 bits) generated by
L<Crypt::URandom>, which reads from the OS cryptographic random
source (C</dev/urandom> on Linux).

=item *

Tokens are stored server-side in the session. They are never
derivable from client-visible data.

=item *

Token comparison uses direct string equality. Timing attacks are
not a practical concern here because the token is rotated after
every check, making any information leaked by timing moot.

=item *

Automatic rotation after C<check_csrf_token> means each token is
single-use. A second submission of the same form (e.g., double-click)
will fail validation.

=back

=head1 SEE ALSO

L<BLM::Startup::BaseSession>, L<BLM::Startup::SessionManager>,
L<Crypt::URandom>, L<Role::Tiny>

=head1 AUTHOR

Rob Lauer - <rlauer6@comcast.net>

=cut
